          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "I’ve caught myself looking in the mirror more. I see that messy, long black hair; outwards lips; outstrut nose; a tall lanky boy, an Asian one, a Taiwanese one. I see those physical features and feel more distance from the ideal but more kinship with the Asian-American. I see my face, I recognize my face. I thought I’d look brave. Maybe a later day."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "When David Mura visited our class, he told me to love my body, “especially as an Asian-American male”. It was difficult to bring those words into my soul, to embrace them. I have always been wary of doing things motivated by my identity as a man, because it’s come to seem that there is no such thing as “toxic masculinity”. It seems that all masculinity, all gendered associations, are either emotionally laborious to the self or harmful to others."
          },
          {
            "type": "graphic",
            "value": {
              "asset": "mapping.html",
              "left": "stoicism, firmness, toughness, boys don’t cry",
              "right": "denying weakness, denying emotion, mental health epidemic"
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "graphic",
            "value": {
              "asset": "mapping.html",
              "left": "powerful, formidable, commanding, provider",
              "right": "violent, subjugating all who are not the “ideal man”: gay, trans, feminine, woman, poor"
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "Some “masculine” qualities, such as being assertive or rational or liking sports, are of course not harmful in themselves. But if you need to <i>be</i> something to <i>be</i> a man, then that something is more often than not disingenuously forced out, and also collectively harmful to those who are unable to meet that. It is the pressuring to do acts associated with manhood, not the acts themselves, that is toxic."
          },
          {
            "type": "graphic",
            "value": {
              "asset": "mapping.html",
              "left": "rational",
              "right": "hyperrational, unsympathetic"
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "graphic",
            "value": {
              "asset": "mapping.html",
              "left": "strong",
              "right": "another mental health epidemic, body image issues, not fat, not skinny, not short, probably not Asian-American"
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "graphic",
            "value": {
              "asset": "mapping.html",
              "left": "caretaker, compassionate, listener",
              "right": "doesn’t need to be just about men anymore, so why is it?"
