            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "<i>Lilting</i> suddenly comes to mind. When I first saw the film, I didn’t know what to think of it. I was only looking at it through the narrow lens of race. I formed some shallow thoughts about the language differences, and how some messages were lost in translation."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "A central point in Feng Cheng’s thesis “Constructing a New Asian Masculinity: Reading <i>Lilting</i> Against Other Films by Asian Filmmakers”<cite>Cheng</cite> is that masculinity in the film"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "Richard does not fit the trope of Americans performatively boasting their ability to use chopsticks."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "Cheng’s ideas made me realize that the reason that the meanings in <i>Lilting </i>had escaped me during my first viewing was that the identities and people in the film were so fluid, so porous."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "***"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "I have the utmost respect for everyone who enabled me to sit and ruminate today: Professor Handal, who manifested this class; my classmates, who inspire me every week; my parents, who are my foundation, my earth; this apartment that is quiet and warm; my friends who make me feel full enough to give myself to this page."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "In inquiring the self, we learn directly about the self, and people, and society."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "I have so much respect and love for those who taught me to, with my great privilege of four years’ time, look up and look within. To think and question and search. But also I must, I must — I must recognize what is around me, and act."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "I am writing this on April 12, 2021. It’s been one day. I am tired of saying the names. Each one carries a deep well of sadness. All I should say here is that today is April 12, 2021. It’s been one day. It’s been two weeks. It’s been, it’s been, it’s been. I feel forced to say a name."
          },
          {
