          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "Daunte Wright. It’s been one day. Today is April 12, 2021. It’s been one day. It’s also been two weeks. It’s also been four weeks. It’s been, it’s been."
          },
          {
            "type": "blockquote",
            "value": "<i>Nobody asked me to. Especially not those for whom it is intended. — Frantz Fanon</i>"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "An Asian-American professor I highly admire recently told me, “[Identity searching is] a process and once you find your place and are comfortable with who you are in your many different surroundings, your purpose will become much clearer.”"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "***"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "I wonder how successful Crazy Rich Asians would have been if the main cast spoke with Chinese accents instead of the Received English."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "Sometimes it’s entertaining to talk in a British accent. But sometimes it’s sickening in the afterthought. The fact that It’s not a symptom, but a marker, of inferiority, of colonization — a pretty equivalent term, though with different connotations in public opinion, is white supremacy. (I say “close” because the terms are too large to be equated, and as such they have different connotations in the public sphere. I don’t say “close” because I think they are different, only because I don’t think I have a full understanding of the two words.) Where does my deep rooted disgust, or fear, come from? I know many immigrants who hope to strip themselves of their Chinese accent as soon as possible. Frantz Fanon studies this phenomenon in the first chapter of <i>Black Skin, White Masks</i>, “The Black Man and Language”:"
          },
          {
            "type": "blockquote",
            "value": "All colonized people —in other words, people in whom an inferiority complex has taken root, whose local cultural originality has been committed to the grave—position themselves in relation to the civilizing language: i.e., the metropolitan culture. The more the colonized has assimilated the cultural values of the metropoli, the more he will have escaped the bush. The more he rejects his blackness and the bush, the whiter he will become."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "Of course, it’s tied to my forced laughter when Asian-American comics make dehumanizing comments in an attempt to be the cool Asian kid who can laugh at racist jokes."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "Like when Ronny Chieng perpetuates the stereotypes that Asians are emotionless, obedient work animals. (I would love to write a rant about the times when Ronny Chieng fronts as disarming Asian stereotypes but actually forwards and strengthens; but this isn’t the place)."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "I see in Ken Jeong’s face the pain of having been that for America. The pain of his Leslie Chow character will lie in history synonymous with Fu Manchu or Charlie Chan: “They’ll throw water at <i>Chow</i> any time.”"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "I’ve seen him play it off at his Netflix special. He says of the criticism from Asian-American fans that they should be proud of him for representing them, for beating up three of “the white man”. He mentions the only criticism one could refute — Asian-American teenage boys who think they can’t sleep with white women because of the small dick stereotype."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "***"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "Professor Manan Ahmed, at a conference he made for his Contemporary Civilization class, said:"
          },
          {
